question:
\begin{array}{l}
\text { B-1. Evaluate }\\
\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty} \int_{0}^{1} \int_{0}^{1} \cdots \int_{0}^{1} \cos ^{2}\left\{\frac{\pi}{2 n}\left(x_{1}+x_{2}+\cdots x_{n}\right)\right\} d x_{1} d x_{2} \cdots d x_{n}
\end{array}

solution:
B-1. The change of variables \( x_{k} \rightarrow 1-x_{k} \) yields
\[
\begin{aligned}
\int_{0}^{1} \int_{0}^{1} \cdots & \int_{0}^{1} \cos ^{2}\left\{\frac{\pi}{2 n}\left(x_{1}+x_{2}+\cdots+x_{n}\right)\right\} d x_{1} d x_{2} \cdots d x_{n} \\
& =\int_{0}^{1} \int_{0}^{1} \cdots \int_{0}^{1} \sin ^{2}\left\{\frac{\pi}{2 n}\left(x_{1}+x_{2}+\cdots+x_{n}\right)\right\} d x_{1} d x_{2} \cdots d x_{n}
\end{aligned}
\]

Each of these expressions, being equal to half their sum, must equal \( \frac{1}{2} \). The limit is also \( \frac{1}{2} \).

